record_data.record_plain_text: -1- 2. Standard Provisions 2.1. Terms and Conditions and Incorporation of Tariff. The terms and conditions under which Network Integration Transmission Service is offered and accepted are pursuant to this NITSA and to the Tariff. The Tariff is hereby incorporated by this reference and made a part of this NITSA. PSE may change the terms and conditions of the Tariff upon, and only upon, approval by the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission (the Commission) pursuant to a filing by PSE. 2.2. Exhibits. The following exhibits to this NITSA are by this reference incorporated herein and made a part hereof: Exhibit A (Specifications for Network Integration Transmission Service); Exhibit B (Methodology for Calculating Power Factor Penalty Adjustment); Exhibit C (Notices); Exhibit D (Forecast of Load); and Exhibit E (Network Operating Agreement). The Parties acknowledge and agree that PSEs Technical Specifications and Operating Protocols and Procedures for Interconnection of Transmission Systems or End-User Loads form part of and are included in the Tariff. 2.3. Completed Application. By receipt of Bonnevilles request for transmission service dated August 22, 2007, PSE has determined that Bonneville has provided a Completed Application for Network Integration Transmission Service under the Tariff. 2.4. System Impact Study. A Study Agreement for a System Impact Study is required for the Application. PSE performed and provided to Bonneville and Kittitas a final System Impact Study, dated May 1, 2010. 2.5. NOA. Pursuant to Section 35 of the Tariff, the Parties are obligated to execute a NOA to address operational and contractual requirements related to Network Integration Transmission Service over PSEs Transmission System. 2.6. Certification of Bonneville. Bonneville certifies that it is, or will be upon commencement of service, an Eligible Customer under the Tariff.

-1- 3. Term and Regulatory Filing 3.1. Effective Date and Filing. This NITSA shall be effective as of the later of (a) ___________, 2010, or (b) such other date as may be designated by the Commission when this NITSA is accepted for filing (Effective Date). PSE shall file this NITSA with the Commission as a NITSA under the Tariff. 3.2. Cancellation Rights. If the Commission determines that any part of this NITSA must be changed, PSE shall offer to Bonneville an amended NITSA reflecting such changes. In the event such amended NITSA is not executed by Bonneville within fifteen (15) days after the Commissions action, this NITSA (as it may be amended pursuant to this Paragraph 3.2) shall be void and have no further force and effect. 3.3. Termination of Agreement. Except as otherwise provided in Paragraph 3.2, this NITSA shall remain in effect through the fifth anniversary of the Effective Date. 3.4. Rollover Rights. Each Party acknowledges and agrees that it enters into this NITSA subject to a right of first refusal and the five-year requirement of Section 2.2 of the Tariff on the first rollover date for this Agreement.

-1- 4. Network Integration Transmission Service 4.1 Network Integration Transmission Service. Commencing on the Effective Date, PSE shall provide to Bonneville, and Bonneville shall receive from PSE and pay for, Network Integration Transmission Service pursuant to the Tariff. PSEs obligation to provide Network Integration Transmission Service shall be subject to PSEs rights to curtail or interrupt schedules pursuant to the Tariff. Exhibit A to this NITSA lists Bonnevilles designated Network Resources and Network Loads. Section 34 of the Tariff outlines the applicable rates and charges methodology for Network Integration Transmission Service. 4.2. Direct Assignment Facilities and Low-Voltage Substation and Distribution Facilities. Exhibit A to this NITSA describes the applicable rates and charges for any Direct Assignment facilities and for transfer service over any low-voltage substation and distribution facilities. 4.3. Power Factor Penalty Adjustment. Power delivered during any hour at each Point of Delivery shall be at a power factor greater than or equal to 0.95, leading or lagging, unless otherwise mutually agreed upon by the Parties. To compensate for deliveries made to a Point of Delivery at a power factor of less than 0.95, leading or lagging, PSE may adjust the billing demand at such Point of Delivery. PSE shall provide one months notice to Bonneville prior to applying for any such penalty adjustment for the first time at a Point of Delivery. Exhibit B, as the same may be amended or modified by PSE and posted on its OASIS from time to time, describes the methodology for calculating a power factor penalty adjustment.

-1- 1. Definitions Unless otherwise defined herein, all capitalized terms used in this NITSA shall have their respective meanings as set forth in the Tariff. For purposes of this NITSA and the Tariff, Bonneville shall be deemed to be the Transmission Customer as such term is used in the Tariff, and PSE shall be deemed to be the Transmission Provider as such term is used in the Tariff.

-1- This NETWORK INTEGRATION TRANSMISSION SERVICE AGREEMENT (NITSA) is dated as of August 24, 2010, by and between PUGET SOUND ENERGY, INC (PSE) and BONNEVILLE POWER ADMINISTRATION (Bonneville). PSE and Bonneville may sometimes be referred to in this Agreement in the singular as a Party and in the plural as Parties. RECITALS WHEREAS, PSE provides Network Integration Transmission Service over its Transmission System under PSEs Open Access Transmission Tariff, FERC Electric Tariff Volume No. 7 (as it may be amended or replaced from time to time, the Tariff); and WHEREAS, Bonneville currently purchases transmission service from PSE to serve the Public Utility District No. 1 of Kittitas County, Washington (Kittitas), pursuant to the NITSA for Firm Point-To-Point Transmission Service under PSEs Tariff (Point-To-Point Agreement); and WHEREAS, Bonneville requested Network Integration Transmission Service from PSE for Kittitas pursuant to the Tariff; and WHEREAS, PSE and Kittitas have entered into an Interconnection and Operating Agreement, dated as of May 28, 2010, providing for the interconnection of PSEs electric system and Kittitas electric system (such agreement, as heretofore or hereafter amended or replaced from time to time, the Interconnection Agreement); and WHEREAS, contemporaneously with entering into this NITSA, the Parties are also entering into a Network Operating Agreement (as it may be amended or replaced from time to time, the NOA), a form of which is attached as Exhibit E to this NITSA, addressing, among other things, operational and contractual requirements related to Network Integration Transmission Service over PSEs Transmission System. NOW THEREFORE, the Parties agree as follows:

EXHIBIT BMETHODOLOGY FOR CALCULATING THE POWER FACTOR PENALTYADJUSTMENT Bonneville shall ensure that operation of the end-user load does not adversely affect the voltage stability of PSEs electric system. Adequate voltage control shall be provided by Bonneville to minimize voltage deviations on the PSE system caused by changing loading conditions. If Bonnevilles end-user load is operating with a power factor less than 0.95, Bonneville will be responsible for installing some type of reactive power compensation to bring the overall power factor up to the 0.95 minimum level, or pay PSE a charge for VAr losses in excess of power factor 0.95. These power factor requirements are to be met at the point of' delivery and/or metering point, during all hours of operation and over all operating conditions. Calculation Methodology for VAr Losses Charge: The compensation formula uses the measured VA and V at the Points of Delivery. The VAr charged to Bonneville is the amount that is higher than 0.95 power factor calculated in each hour. The VAr flow higher than 0.95 power factor in a given hour would be either from PSE to the Interconnection Customer, or from the Interconnection Customer to PSE. The formula for VAr losses when VAr flow measured is from PSE to the Interconnection Customer is: VArloss = VArin-to-load W x 0.3287 The formula for VAr losses when VAr flow measured is from the Interconnection Customer to PSE is: VArloss = VArout-of-load W x 0.3287 Where VArin-to-load, VArout-of-load, and W are as measured at each Point of Delivery. The W x 0.3287 term credits VAr consumption by the Interconnection Customer down to a power factor of 0.95. In each hour, the VArloss is calculated by the above formula. When the calculated VArloss is a positive number it is accumulated with all other positive VArloss in the metering period, and multiplied by the VAr charge per kVArH. Examples of conditions with VArs in-to-load and VArs out-of-load are given in the following: Sample Calculations Example: VArs in-to-load for 1 hour Power Factor (p.f.) 80% Vary = tan(cos-1p.f.) x W Real Power 3,500,000 watts (W) Reactive Power 2,625,000 Voltage-Ampere reactive (VAr) VArloss = VArin-to-generator W x 0.3287 = 2,625,000 1,150,450 = 1,474,550 kVarH VAr Charge per kVArH 0.098 Cents VAr Hourly Charge $1.45 Example: VArs out-of-load for 1 hour Power Factor 90% Real Power 2,500,000 watts (W) Reactive Power 1,210,805 Voltage-Ampere reactive (VAr) Formula for VAr losses: VArloss = VArin-to-generator = W x 0.3287 = 1,210,805 821,750 = 389,055 kVarH VAr Charge per kVArH 0.098 Cents VAr Hourly Charge $0.38

8. Miscellaneous Provisions 8.1. Interconnection with Other Systems. Nothing contained in this NITSA shall restrict or limit either Party from establishing, altering or terminating interconnection points with any entity not a party to this NITSA or amending or entering into such agreements; provided, that PSE, during the term of this NITSA, shall not amend or terminate the Interconnection Agreement or grant new interconnections to Kittitas without the prior written approval of Bonneville. 8.2. Future Changes or Additions. Future changes or additions that increase PSEs Transmission System capability shall not obligate PSE to provide any transmission or other services in addition to those services provided under this NITSA, except by separate Application pursuant to Section 31.2 of the Tariff; provided, however, that this Section 8.2 does not modify PSEs obligation to provide Network Integration Transmission Service for Network Load designated pursuant to Section 31 of the Tariff. 8.3. Waivers. Any waiver at any time by either Party hereto of its rights with respect to the other Party or with respect to any matter arising in connection with this NITSA shall not be considered a waiver with respect to any other default of the same or any other matter. 8.4. Effect of Paragraph Headings. Headings and captions appearing in this NITSA are inserted for convenience of reference only and shall not be construed to be interpretations of the text of this NITSA. 8.5. Assignment. PSE may assign this NITSA only upon the prior written consent of Bonneville, provided, however, that Bonneville hereby consents to assignment of this NITSA to a successor of PSE that acquires all or substantially all of PSEs electric transmission assets. Bonneville and Kittitas may request an assignment of this NITSA from Bonneville to Kittitas. This assignment shall include all rights and post-assignment obligations associated with this NITSA. Such assignment shall require mutual agreement among PSE, Bonneville and Kittitas, provided that PSE shall not unreasonably withhold such agreement. When notice of such assignment is provided to PSE, Bonneville and Kittitas shall work in good faith to make any necessary modifications to this NITSA and the NOA, implement metering modifications, ensure compliance with the Tariff, and make any other adjustments necessary to allow such assignment to proceed. If PSE withholds agreement to such assignment, PSE shall provide a detailed written explanation as to why it is withholding agreement and shall include a detailed list of items that would allow PSE to agree to such assignment. A Party requesting assignment shall provide at least six months prior written notice to the other Party. Any assignment pursuant to this Section 8.5 by an assignor to an assignee shall only be made with the contemporaneous assignment of the NOA pursuant to Section 11.3 of the NOA by the same assignor to the same assignee. Subject to the foregoing restrictions on assignment, this NITSA shall be binding upon, inure to the benefit of and be enforceable by the Parties and their successors and assigns. 8.6. Notices. Any notice or request made to or by either Party regarding this NITSA shall be directed to the representative of the other Party as indicated in Exhibit C. 8.7. Notices of an Operating Nature. Any notice or request pertaining to matters of an operating or maintenance nature, or of a routine character pertaining to delivery or receipt of power, shall be given in such manner as the Parties from time to time shall agree upon. 8.8. Relationship of Bonneville and Kittitas under the NITSA and NOA. With respect to determining the rights and obligations of PSE under this NITSA actions or functions by Bonneville under this NITSA or the NOA shall be deemed, and PSE may rely on their being deemed, to be on behalf of Kittitas; provided, however, that, nothing in this NITSA or the NOA (a) shall be construed as creating any obligation of Bonneville enforceable by Kittitas and/or (b) confer upon Kittitas any third-party beneficiary rights.
